05241nam a22009255i 9780231511582DE-B159720190708092533.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190708s2007    nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802315115827 a10.7312/pres140122doi  a(DE-B1597)459232  a(OCoLC)1013953669  a(OCoLC)1037972614  a(OCoLC)1041973619  a(OCoLC)1046609335  a(OCoLC)1047017936  a(OCoLC)1049624419  a(OCoLC)1054870252  a(OCoLC)979628633  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aDS135.G33 P67 2007 7aLIT0000002bisacsh04a303.483209431 aPresner, Todd, eauthor.10aMobile Modernity :bGermans, Jews, Trains /cTodd Presner. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2007] 4c©2007  a1 online resource :b29 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCultures of History00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. Dialectics at a Standstill -- t2. Berlin and Delos -- t3. Sicily, New York City, and the Baranovich Station -- t4. The North Sea -- t5. Nuremberg-Fürth-Palestine -- t6. Auschwitz -- t7. Vienna-Rome-Prague-Antwerp-Paris -- tConcluding Remarks -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThough the history of the German railway system is often associated with the transportation of Jews to labor and death camps, Todd Presner looks instead to the completion of the first German railway lines and their role in remapping the cultural geography and intellectual history of Germany's Jews. Treating the German railway as both an iconic symbol of modernity and a crucial social, technological, and political force, Presner advances a groundbreaking interpretation of the ways in which mobility is inextricably linked to German and Jewish visions of modernity. Moving beyond the tired model of a failed German-Jewish dialogue, Presner emphasizes the mutual entanglement of the very categories of German and Jewish and the many sites of contact and exchange that occurred between German and Jewish thinkers.Turning to philosophy, literature, and the history of technology, and drawing on transnational cultural and diaspora studies, Presner charts the influence of increased mobility on interactions between Germans and Jews. He considers such major figures as Kafka, Heidegger, Arendt, Freud, Sebald, Hegel, and Heine, reading poetry next to philosophy, architecture next to literature, and railway maps next to cultural history. Rather than a conventional, linear history that culminates in the tragedy of the Holocaust, Presner produces a cultural mapping that articulates a much more complex story of the hopes and catastrophes of mobile modernity. By focusing on the spaces of encounter emblematically represented by the overdetermined triangulation of Germans, Jews, and trains, he introduces a new genealogy for the study of European and German-Jewish modernity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 08. Jul 2019) 0aGerman literaturexJewish authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aJewsxCultural assimilationzGermany. 0aJewszGermanyxIdentity. 0aJewszGermanyxIntellectual lifey19th century. 0aJewszGermanyxIntellectual lifey20th century. 0aTechnology and civilization. 0aTechnologyxSocial aspects. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066254208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044247208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2014z978311045952440uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/pres14012423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780231511582.jpg  a978-3-11-044247-2  CUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013  a978-3-11-045952-4  CUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2014c2000d2014  a9